Let's also look at the amount of land required to produce foods: 

On just 2.5 acres of land, 23 people can be fed on cabbage, 22 on lettuce, 19 on Rice, 17 on Corn, 15 on Wheat, 2 on Chicken, 2 on Milk, 1 person on eggs, and only 1 person on Beef.

For every calorie of food, it takes only 2 calories of fuel to produce Soy, 3 to produce Corn, 3 to produce Wheat, and 54 to produce Meat. That's a 2600% increase just for meat! 

So yes when I said that it is inefficient converting calories of grain to produce meat, this is partly why. Chickens & pigs convert grain into meat at rates of 2 to 1, or 3 to 1 (ie, it takes 2kg of feed to produce 1kg of chicken). The ratio for lamb is between 4:1 and over 6:1 & that for beef starts at 5:1 and goes as high as 20:1. Meat is an inefficient source of calories, case closed. It accounts for 17% of global calorific intake, but uses twice that amount of land, water and feed. 

And here's the other part why:
Not all of the cow makes it to the table. On avg, a 1,000 lb steer will only weigh 61% of its live weight once it makes it to the rail. This approximate 39% loss during the slaughter & dressing procedure
is a result of the animal being bled & the hide, head, hooves, viscera, lung & heart being removed. The remaining 61% is referred to as "Hanging Weight" or the weight "On the Rail". But the loss doesn't stop there. Once the carcass is on the rail, it begins to leach moisture (shrink) which accounts for additional weight loss. This along with fat and bone removed during the cutting account for an 18% loss. In summary, a steer averaging 1,000 lbs on the hoof will avg around 430 lbs of retail cuts ( steaks, roasts, ground beef, stew beef, etc.) 

Again, very wasteful and inefficient. I think I'll stick to my beans, veggies, and potatoes.

